  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane's inner east is one of the most concentrated pockets of character housing in Australia. Queenslanders, worker's cottages, post-war chamferboard homes, and interwar bungalows line the streets of Morningside, Camp Hill, Norman Park, Hawthorne, Balmoral, and Coorparoo. These homes do not appraise, market, or sell the same way a 2010 brick-and-tile does, and treating them as though they do is one of the most common mistakes vendors make when choosing how to sell.</p>

      <p>Character homes attract a specific and passionate buyer pool, and understanding who those buyers are and what they value is the foundation of a successful campaign. It also shapes how you price, how you present, and what building and pest issues you need to deal with before you go to market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What counts as a Queenslander or character home</h2>
      <p>The term "character home" is used loosely in real estate, but in Brisbane it generally means a pre-1946 timber home with features not found in modern construction: VJ-lined walls (vertical jointed tongue-and-groove timber), high ceilings (often 10 to 12 feet), wide covered verandahs, timber floors, casement or awning windows, and elevated subfloor construction on timber or concrete stumps. Queenslanders are the most recognised subtype, identifiable by their wide verandahs and high-set construction designed to maximise airflow in subtropical conditions.</p>

      <p>Not every old timber home qualifies as a character home in the buyer's mind. Homes that have been heavily renovated and stripped of original features, or that have had original materials replaced with modern substitutes, often lose the premium that genuine character buyers will pay. The presence of original VJ walls, ceilings, and joinery matters far more to this buyer pool than granite benchtops or a rainwater shower.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How character homes are valued differently</h2>
      <p>Standard comparable sales analysis works less well for character homes, because the spread of outcomes between a well-presented character home and a poorly maintained one is much wider than for modern homes. A renovated Queenslander in Norman Park with an intact original facade, updated kitchen and bathrooms, and a sensible rear extension will attract entirely different buyers and prices than a structurally sound but unimproved version of the same home three streets away.</p>

      <p>The key value drivers are not square metres of living space. They are the quality and integrity of original features, the quality of any renovation work done, aspect and airflow, land size, proximity to good schools, and whether the home has been extended in a way that respects its character. A poor rear addition that compromises the original roofline or covers the back verandah can actively reduce value compared to an unimproved home with a clear renovation pathway for the next buyer.</p>

      <p>Land content matters more for character homes than for modern townhouses or apartments, because many buyers are purchasing both the existing home and the option to improve or extend it. Inner east blocks of 500 square metres and above, particularly north to east facing, carry a meaningful premium when combined with a character home that has room to grow.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The buyer pool for character homes</h2>
      <p>The buyers who seek character homes are not just buying a house. They are buying a lifestyle, an aesthetic, and in many cases a renovation project they have been planning for years. These buyers tend to be older, equity-rich, and patient. They have often been watching the character home market in their target suburbs for twelve months or more. They are less sensitive to interest rate cycles than first-home buyers, and they will pay a premium for the right home in the right location rather than settling for a modern substitute.</p>

      <p>Reaching this buyer pool requires being where they look. Character home buyers tend to be active on Domain and realestate.com.au, but they also respond well to targeted social media, suburb-specific email marketing, and word-of-mouth. Many of the best results for Queenslanders and character homes in Brisbane's inner east come from buyers who were already aware of the property before the official campaign launched, because the agent had the relationships and the database to create pre-market interest.</p>

      <p>There is also a builder and developer buyer pool for some character properties, particularly those on larger blocks with wide street frontages in development-zoned corridors. These buyers see the home differently. They are interested in the land value and the development potential, not the character features. Occasionally this buyer pool sets the price; more often, the emotional premium paid by a genuine character buyer exceeds what a developer will offer. Understanding which pool will drive your result is part of the agent's job before you set a price guide.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What building inspectors flag on character homes</h2>
      <p>Character homes generate longer building and pest reports than modern homes. This is not necessarily a sign the home is in poor condition. It reflects the age of the building and the different construction standards of the era. As a vendor, understanding what inspectors typically flag helps you decide what to address before your campaign and what to leave for buyers to factor into their offers.</p>

      <p>Subfloor moisture is the most common issue in Brisbane character homes. Elevated construction means good airflow in most conditions, but low-set extensions and enclosed subfloors can trap moisture, leading to timber decay, subfloor fungal growth, and occasionally termite activity. A subfloor inspection and remediation before going to market is one of the best pre-sale investments for a character home. It removes a large and often emotionally charged item from the buyer's report.</p>

      <p>Asbestos is present in many pre-1980 Brisbane homes, particularly in wet areas and external cladding. This does not disqualify a home from selling, but it needs to be disclosed, and buyers will often price it in if they discover it themselves rather than having it disclosed upfront. Having an asbestos register prepared before your campaign and presenting it transparently demonstrates confidence and reduces negotiating leverage for buyers who might otherwise use it to discount.</p>

      <p>Stump condition is significant in high-set character homes. Timber stumps have a lifespan and may need partial or full replacement. Concrete stumps are more durable but can crack or settle. The cost of restumping a full-size Queenslander can run to $30,000 to $60,000, which is material enough that buyers will use it in negotiation if it appears in their report. Again, having an independent assessment done beforehand gives you accurate information to work with rather than leaving it to the buyer's inspector to frame the issue.</p>

      <p>Wiring and plumbing in pre-war homes is often original or mixed-era. Buyers' conveyancers and lenders are increasingly attentive to electrical compliance, particularly in homes with original knob-and-tube wiring or ungrounded circuits. Electrical upgrades are not always required to sell, but an electrician's report that confirms the current state puts you in a stronger position than leaving buyers to assume the worst.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Presenting and photographing a character home</h2>
      <p>Character homes photograph differently from modern homes. The features that buyers love, original VJ walls, pressed-metal ceilings, timber floors, and period joinery, can be difficult to capture well with standard real estate photography. They require natural light, wide-angle lenses used carefully, and a photographer who understands how to make warm timber tones read as inviting rather than dark.</p>

      <p>The styling approach for character homes should work with the original features, not against them. This is not the context for a monochrome Scandi look or industrial-style furniture. Buyers looking at Queenslanders and character homes are drawn to warmth, comfort, and a sense of home that feels connected to the building's history. Timber furniture, natural textiles, indoor plants, and vintage or classic decorative elements support that response. Stagers who work regularly in the inner east understand this; those who work predominantly in new developments often do not.</p>

      <p>The subfloor, yard, and original facade are as important as the interior for character home buyers. A well-maintained garden that lets the home's architecture breathe, a freshly painted facade in a period-appropriate colour, and clean and safe subfloor access all contribute to the impression that the home has been cared for, which is the foundational message you want buyers to leave with.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where character homes command the strongest premiums</h2>
      <p>Within Brisbane's inner east, the suburbs where character home premiums are most pronounced are Norman Park, Hawthorne, Balmoral, and Bulimba at the top end, followed closely by Camp Hill, Morningside, and Coorparoo. These suburbs combine school catchment appeal (Lourdes Hill, Cannon Hill Anglican, Morningside State, Camp Hill State Infants and Primary) with walkable village strips, river proximity or views, and a stock of quality character homes dense enough that buyers specifically target the suburb rather than just accepting it.</p>

      <p>Annerley, Dutton Park, and Woolloongabba also have significant character home stock and are commanding increasing premiums as buyers are priced out of the premium inner-east suburbs. The character home premium there is often underestimated, which creates genuine opportunity for vendors who price carefully and present well.</p>

